05→    // Since newTaskId is new, we check if any dep's transitive deps include any task\n   106→    // that depends on newTaskId. But since newTaskId is new, no existing task can depend on it.\n   107→    // So we only need to check: do any of the dependencies form a cycle among themselves?\n   108→    // Actually, we also need to check: do tasks that depend on us (none yet since new) ...\n   109→    // For a new task, cycle detection means: can we reach newTaskId from any of the deps?\n   110→    // Since newTaskId isn't in the graph yet, the answer is always no for a new task.\n   111→    // But we should check for cycles among the provided dependencies themselves.\n   112→\n   113→    // Actually the real check is: do any of the tasks that we'll eventually unblock\n   114→    // already transitively depend on one of our dependencies?\n   115→    // Since this task is new, no one depends on it yet. So no cycle from a new task.\n   116→    // However, we should also think about: what if dep A depends on dep B and dep B depends on dep A?\n   117→    // That's not our problem to detect here - that would have been caught when they were created.\n   118→\n   119→    // The main cycle case: task depends on itself\n   120→    if (dependencies.includes(newTaskId)) return true;\n   121→\n   122→    // For existing tasks that we depend on: check if they (transitively) depend on each other\n   123→    // in a way that would create a cycle. But again, since we're new, no cycle is possible\n   124→    // unless we depend on ourselves.\n   125→\n   126→    // Wait - there's another case: what if we're adding task C that depends on B,\n   127→    // and later someone adds task D that depends on C and A, where A depends on D?\n   128→    // That would be caught when D is added. So for a new task, we only need to\n   129→    // worry about self-dependency.\n   130→\n   131→    // Actually re-reading the requirements: \"Circular dependencies (direct or indirect)\n   132→    // mus